==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|aberrātus}}, perfect passive participle of {{m|la|aberrō||wander, stray or deviate from}}, formed from {{m|la|ab||from, away from}} + {{m|la|errō||stray}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ˈæb.ə.ɹeɪt/|lang=en}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|aberrat}}

# {{lbl|en|intransitive}} To go [[astray]]; to [[diverge]]; to [[deviate]] (from); deviate from. {{defdate|mid 18the century}}<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=4}}</ref>
#* '''1839''', {{w|Thomas De Quincey}}, “Lake Reminiscences: No. V, Southey, Wordsworth, and Coleridge” originally published in ''{{w|Tait's Magazine|Tait’s Magazine}}'', August 1839, in {{w|David Masson}} (editor), ''The Collected Writings of Thomas De Quincey'', London: A. & C. Black, 1896, Volume 2, Chapter 5, pp. 340-341,<sup>[https://archive.org/details/collectedwriting02dequuoft]</sup>
#*: {{...}} the barriers, which to them limit the view, and give to it, together with the contraction, all the distinctness and definite outline of limitation, are, in nine cases out of ten, the product of their own defective and '''aberrating''' vision, and not real barriers at all.
# {{lbl|en|transitive}} To [[distort]]; to cause [[aberration]] of. {{defdate|late 19th century}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* '''1893''', {{w|Bret Harte}}, ''Sally Dows'', Chapter 6, in ''Sally Dows and Other Stories'', Boston: Houghton Mifflin, p. 104,<sup>[https://archive.org/details/sallydowsandothe00hartiala]</sup>
#*: He saw them through no '''aberrating''' mist of tenderness or expediency—but with the single directness of the man of action.
#* '''1918''', {{w|Theodore Dreiser}}, “The Lost Phœbe” in ''Free and Other Stories'', New York: Boni and Liveright, p. 122,<sup>[https://archive.org/details/freeotherstories00dreiuoft]</sup>
#*: He and Phœbe had had a senseless quarrel {{...}} and she had left. It was an '''aberrated''' fulfillment of her old jesting threat that if he did not behave himself she would leave him.

====Usage notes====
* The transitive sense is chiefly used in the past participle form (as ''[[aberrated]]'').

